    <text>
        <body>
            <div>

                <opener>
                    <salute>My Lord</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Give me leave to present your Grace with a copy of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0001">my tour thro Scotland</title>
                    </bibl>, as a poor mark of the
                    sense I have of the hospitable reception I met with at <placeName ref="pl0110">Athol House</placeName>, &amp; the favors I received since. I flatter
                    myself That your Grace will think <persName ref="pe0143">my Engraver</persName>
                    has done justice to the Drawings.<note type="editorial">
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Pennant</persName> is probably referring to two drawings of scenes on
                        the <placeName ref="pl0821">Atholl estate</placeName> originally taken by
                            <persName ref="pe0330">Paul Sandby</persName>, that were reproduced in
                        the first edition of the <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0001">
                                <hi rend="italic">Tour in Scotland 1769</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl>: see <rs type="art" ref="ar0094">'Dunkeld Cathedral' (Plate II., p.75)</rs> and
                            <rs type="art" ref="ar0095">'View near Blair' (Plate IV., p.98)</rs>.
                        Pennant's letters on 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> August 1772 and 21<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> April 1774, suggest that the Duke was
                        disappointed by Pennant's reuse of Sandby's views.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It is with great impatience I wish to make another visit to <placeName ref="pl0705">N. Britain</placeName> &amp; to ramble thro those parts that I
                    did not see in 1769. If I may presume so far I should think myself highly
                    honored by recommendations to such parts as your influence extends; for there is
                    no travelling with convenience or edification without Letters.<note type="editorial">
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Pennant</persName> would make a
                        second tour of <placeName ref="pl0705">Scotland</placeName> in summer
                        1772.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Please to do me the honor to present my respectfull compliments to <persName ref="pe0577">the Dutchess</persName> &amp; think me with great regard</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>My Lord <lb/>Your much obliged &amp; <lb/>most obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> humble Servant</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Thomas Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="pl0001">Downing Flintshire</placeName> Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                        1771.</dateline>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P.S. Should your Grace happen to be in <placeName ref="pl0699">London</placeName>, <persName ref="pe0026">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> White Bookseller in Fleetstreet</persName> will obey the
                        inclosed order.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
